		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Legal issues</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />There are legal issues about ROMs and emulators.<br />The reason why I'm posting this is because I believe that this issue has already been resolved and I want to get direct information about it.<br /><br />This is how I believe:<br />Software is protected by copyright that lasts 75 years after author's death.<br />Hardware is protected by patents that last 15 years after issuing.<br />This means that all hardware before 2000 is legal to be modded.<br />By default, ROMs can only be dumped if you are the copyright holder or the license grants the permission to do so or if you already have the game.<br />However, the evil greedy License Agreements have bigger power over the third default. Nintendo explicitly forbids all ROMs on their legal site.<br />Forbidding emulators is however beyond their control because the patents have expired.<br /><br />Now I don't know what exactly is actually legal. Can you help me? Please correct me if there's some incorrect about what I said. I've seen Mario ROMs and Mario hacks and they are all so awesome and I don't want to throw them away because they're derivative work.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tepples</b> [ Fri Mar 13, 2015 4:13 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Legal issues</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />If you're starting a business, run your business plan past a lawyer. I sure ain't one.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">8bitMicroGuy wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">This is how I believe:<br />Software is protected by copyright that lasts 75 years after author's death.</div><br />In which country? In most, it's life plus 70.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Hardware is protected by patents that last 15 years after issuing.</div><br />Current U.S. law is 20 years after filing, with possibility of up to a 5-year extension for undue USPTO delay or FDA marketing approval.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">By default, ROMs can only be dumped if you are the copyright holder or the license grants the permission to do so or if you already have the game.</div><br />At least in the USA, it's not an infringement for the owner of a copy of a video game to use a copying device to dump the ROM for use with a computer, so long as he does not share this copy with anyone else. (17 USC 117) Shrinkwrap EULAs on console games sold as physical copies tend to run up against &quot;privity&quot; limits of contract law.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Now I don't know what exactly is actually legal. Can you help me? Please correct me if there's some incorrect about what I said. I've seen Mario ROMs and Mario hacks and they are all so awesome and I don't want to throw them away because they're derivative work.</div><br />ROM hacks are probably illegal to distribute. However, Nintendo has tended to look the other way at RomHacking.net because there are bigger legal fish to fry. Ideally, some of the ROM hackers would pool their efforts and create an original engine as a basis for total conversions instead of using SMB1, SMB3, and SMW all the time.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


